{
  "text": "In the BR.21 study, elderly patients (aged \u226570 years) had more severe (grade 3 or 4) AEs compared with younger patients (aged <70 years) (35 vs. 18%, respectively; P<0.001) [CITATION_1] . In our study, 11 patients (29%) had grade 3 AEs, most of which were managed via dose reductions. Grade 4 or 5 AEs were not observed. Two patients had grade 3 interstitial pneumonitis and were treated with corticosteroid therapy. The frequency of AEs in our study was not higher compared with the previously reported frequencies (28.1-35%) [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Therefore, erlotinib appears to be well-tolerated in elderly patients with previously treated NSCLC.",
